ings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vauncey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  See  Dancey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dancey","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): variant of   Dansie  ."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Edmund De Vauncey was born in 1339, in Westley Waterless, Cambridgeshire, England. He married Aubigny Creake in 1354, in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1361, in England, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1339–1361":"1339–1361","1330–1355":"1330–1355","1355–1397":"1355–1397","1364–1399":"1364–1399","1355":"1355","1399":"1399","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1339":